\b SUB:\b0\tab Proposal: Aerial Laser Cannon\par
\par
This is one of several proposals I'm submitting for the research and development of new laser weaponry. Each of these will have to be developed separately due to the size differences, power levels and complexity of the systems involved.\par
\par
The Aerial Laser Cannon is the largest and most powerful iteration of our new laser designs. Like our infantry weapons it'll be powered by deuterium-fluoride reaction, but on a much larger scale and amplified by the aircraft's on-board electrical systems. Several exciting ideas are being considered.\par
\par
As well as being the biggest, this may well be our most challenging laser to create. Any aircraft cannon will have to reach across several kilometres of atmosphere -- and therefore loads of atmospheric blooming -- with enough punch at the endpoint to cut into a UFO's fuselage. Those sorts of power levels have been achieved before with massive arrays mounted on jumbo jets, but never in a package small enough to make a jet fighter cannon.\par
\par
The finished product should be able to engage UFOs with bullseye accuracy at ranges well beyond that of the SHIVA cannon, and although damage may be low, we expect that the ability to keep continuous fire and pressure on enemy craft will be valuable in the days to come.\par
\par
Please approve lab time and funding for this program when you're ready, Commander.\par
\par
--Cdr. Navarre\par
\par
\par
\b TO:\tab\b0 Base Commander, PHALANX, Atlantic Operations Command\par
\b FROM:\b0\tab Cdr. Paul Navarre, R&D: Engineering Division, PHALANX, Atlantic Operations Command\par
\b DATE:\b0\tab %02i %s %i\par
\b SUB:\b0\tab Re: Aerial Laser Cannon\par
\par
Commander, I've just finished my report on our latest laser program. We've successfully prototyped the new Aerial Laser Cannon and are ready to put it into production.\par
\par
We achieved what we set out to do: create a continuous wave, deuterium-fluoride-powered laser with megawatt-range output, capable of tracking and hitting UFOs at ranges of up to 5 kilometres. Accuracy is excellent, hampered only by enemy ECM (Electronic Countermeasures), and unlike our other weapons the ALC's accuracy is unaffected by distance. The laser proceeds to the target in a straight line at the speed of light; it's hard to miss with it.\par
\par
Unfortunately atmospheric blooming is still a problem, and the beam rapidly loses power the further it has to travel. At maximum range, 5 kilometres, it takes 32 seconds of continuous fire on the same spot to penetrate a UFO's hull. We're rarely going to have that much time to wait for a kill. The ideal range for this weapon is between 2 to 3 kilometres where it strikes a good balance between damage and distance. Average damage per second at these distances is slightly less than the SHIVA Rotary Cannon, but range is longer by up to 1.5 kilometres. More so than any of our previous aircraft weapons, the ALC is ideal for driving and pinning down the enemy, using either rapid pulses or continuous fire.\par
\par
The cannon carries an integrated magazine of deuterium-fluoride allowing up to thirty minutes of continuous fire. Since deuterium and fluoride are both too potentially hazardous to store on-base, and we have access to large off-base stockpiles of all the necessary compounds, we will not need to keep laser cannon ammunition in inventory.\par
\par
Deployment is at your discretion, Commander, but I'd like to recommend we use the ALC to replace most of our old SHIVA guns except for craft specifically equipped for close-in fighting. The laser offers far better accuracy in any craft slower than a UFO, and with nearly as much staying power as the SHIVA it should perform very well in all its intended roles.\par
\par
--Cdr. Navarre\lang2057\b\f1\fs24\par
