\b TO:\tab\b0 Base Commander, PHALANX, Atlantic Operations Command\par
\b FROM:\b0\tab Cdr. Paul Navarre, R&D: Engineering Division, PHALANX, Atlantic Operations Command\par
\b DATE:\b0\tab %02i %s %i\par
\b SUB:\b0\tab Re: Alien Launcher\par
\par
Commander, we've finished work on the alien missile launcher. Here is my report.\par
\par
The launcher itself is a fairly simple affair. Firing is computer-driven, fed directly from the UFO's targeting computer. Powerful electromagnetic coils around the launch tube accelerate the missile to extreme speeds, reaching up to Mach 4 at the point where the missile leaves the tube. Only once a missile is fully free of the tube are its onboard rockets allowed to kick in. After that the missile is on its own, fully independent of the UFO and its targeting computer.\par
\par
The good news is that we've managed to succesfully adapt fittings, controls and power feeds to allow the Alien Launcher to be safely mounted to our aircraft. The bad news is that we've had to drastically reduce its magazine size in order to meet weight and size restrictions on our aircraft.\par
\par
Where a UFO can easily carry and secure up to 16 missiles in an internal magazine, our aircraft are too small and light to be able to carry so many, and most of our craft aren't laid out with internal missile magazines. We've had to custom-build a magazine mounted with the launcher, its ammo capacity no larger than 8 missiles, but we reckon it's a lot better than nothing.\par
\par
We also believe that we can modify the launch tube to be able to fire human missiles as well as alien types. We'd have to develop the missiles ourselves, of course -- no current human missile is capable of withstanding the stress of being fired from this launcher. However, we're confident we can create a design that will survive the launcher and incorporates new UFO-tracking technologies to improve accuracy.\par
\par
I'll send you a design proposal as soon as I can, Commander.\par
\par
--Cdr. Navarre\lang2057\b\f1\fs24\par
