Commander, these blueprints are an amazing refinement of the Bolter Rifle concept. Instead of a muzzle-loading EM assault rifle, the Russians have turned this into a belt-fed electromagnetic machine gun.\par
\par
After each round is fired, a powerful spring mechanism jumps forward and pushes the rails out of the way to make room for another round. The revolving magnet drops the new round in the barrel, the spring releases, the old rails snuggle up with the new piece and the oldest piece is ejected out of the front. Then the magnet creates a barrel seal and the weapon is ready to fire.\par
\par
The gun can be hazardous to bystanders because it's constantly vomiting hot chunks of molten EM rail out of the barrel. It's also extremely power-hungry, requiring a massive battery worn like a backpack just to fire one full belt. Once the belt is gone, there's no chance for a battlefield reload. This can become a problem given the rate at which the Machine Bolter chews up ammo. No soldier should be given a Machine Bolter without some kind of backup weapon.\par
\par
That makes two considerable limitations to an otherwise amazing weapon. I think we should start deploying this right away to test its effectiveness and then see if it's worthwhile for continued deployment.\par
\par
