\par
Another one of the interesting topics in our UN files is the production of human powered armour. These are suits where much of the usual muscle-work of the soldier is taken over by advanced servomotors, many times more powerful than human muscle tissue. Soldiers wearing a suit of powered armour would be faster, stronger, capable of making powerful jumps and falls that would turn an unarmoured human to pulp.\par
\par
The problem with these suits has always been the difficulty of building powerful servos into a suit small enough to be worn effectively by a human being. Powered armour has been around as a concept for more than a century, and has seen plenty of use in recent conflicts, but it has yet to materialise in a form that's useful for close quarters urban combat. Current-generation military suits have more in common with tanks than infantry and can't possibly meet our mobility and space requirements.\par
\par
The research files feature many designs ranging from unarmoured exoskeletons to fully-enclosing 'spacesuits'. We'd like to organise a new research project to sort out the raw data and combine the most promising ideas into an effective powersuit for our soldiers.\par
\par
--Cdr. Navarre\par
